	<article class="post-606324 post type-post status-publish hentry category-financial-services category-investment-banking category-legal tag-banking-and-financial-institutions tag-federal-reserve-system tag-regulation-and-deregulation-of-industry tag-tarullo-daniel-k tag-united-states-economy tag-yellen-janet-l per-tarullo-daniel-k per-yellen-janet-l des-banking-and-financial-institutions des-regulation-and-deregulation-of-industry des-united-states-economy org-federal-reserve-system" id="post-606324">
	<header class="postHeader">
				<div class="postKicker">
			<span class="kicker"><a href="https://dealbook.nytimes.com/category/main-topics/investment-banking/">Investment Banking</a> | <a href="https://dealbook.nytimes.com/category/main-topics/legal/">Legal/Regulatory</a></span>		</div>
				<h1 itemprop="headline" class="entry-title">Yellen Suggests That Fed Will Push to Shore Up Market for Short-Term Debt</h1>
		<div class="story-meta-footer">
			<address class="byline author vcard" itemprop="author creator" itemtype="//schema.org/Person">
				By Peter Eavis			</address>
			<!-- date published --><time class="dateline " datetime="2014-04-15T21:15:55+00:00" itemprop="datePublished">April 15, 2014 5:15 pm</time>
			<!-- date updated --><span class="visually-hidden updated">April 15, 2014 5:15 pm</span><button class="button comments-button  theme-kicker" data-skip-to-para-id="">
</button>
		</div>
			</header>
		<div class="entry-content">
	<div class="w592"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="associatedMedia" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/04/16/business/BANK/BANK-tmagArticle.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/04/16/business/BANK/BANK-tmagArticle.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/04/16/business/BANK/BANK-tmagArticle.jpg" id="100000002827536" width="592" height="395" alt="Janet L. Yellen, chairwoman of the Federal Reserve, said on Tuesday that banks may be required to hold more capital."   /><meta itemprop="height" content="395"><meta itemprop="width" content="592"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">Janet L. Yellen, chairwoman of the Federal Reserve, said on Tuesday that banks may be required to hold more capital.</span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Paul Beaty/Associated Press</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<div id="sharetools-story" class="sharetools theme-classic sharetools-story" data-shares="email|Email,facebook|Share,twitter|Tweet,save|Save,show-all|More,ad" data-url="https://dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/04/15/fed-weighing-new-rules-on-short-term-borrowing-yellen-says/" data-title="Yellen Suggests That Fed Will Push to Shore Up Market for Short-Term Debt" data-description=" The chairwoman of the Federal Reserve said that the Fed was actively considering measures to strengthen that potential weak spot.">
				<div class="ad sharetools-inline-article-ad"></div>
				<div id="MiddleLeft" class="ad middle-left-ad nocontent robots-nocontent"></div>
				</div><p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">A crucial part of Wall Street still keeps federal regulators up at night. But Janet L. Yellen, the chairwoman of the <a href="//topics.nytimes.com/top/reference/timestopics/organizations/f/federal_reserve_system/index.html?inline=nyt-org" class="tickerized" title="More articles about the Federal Reserve System.">Federal Reserve</a>, said on Tuesday that the Fed was actively considering measures to strengthen that potential weak spot.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Ms. Yellen said that despite an onslaught of new bank regulations, risks remained in the markets where Wall Street firms and other entities lend and borrow hundreds of billions of dollars for short periods. The 2008 financial crisis showed that these gigantic markets were particularly susceptible to panic. With that in mind, <a href="//www.federalreserve.gov/newsevents/speech/yellen20140415a.htm" title="Video and text of Yellen's speech"> Ms. Yellen suggested some measures on Tuesday</a> that could restrain the use of short-term borrowing at the largest banks â including requiring them to hold more capital.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âThere might be room for stronger capital and liquidity standards for large banks than have been adopted so far,â Ms. Yellen said in a prerecorded speech to the Federal Reserve Bank of Atlantaâs Financial Markets Conference. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><webonly><object id="flashObj" width="250" height="220" classid="clsid:D27CDB6E-AE6D-11cf-96B8-444553540000" codebase="//download.macromedia.com/pub/shockwave/cabs/flash/swflash.cab#version=9,0,47,0"><param name="movie" value="//c.brightcove.com/services/viewer/federated_f9?isVid=1&#038;isUI=1" /><param name="bgcolor" value="#FFFFFF" /><param name="flashVars" value="videoId=3467835402001&#038;playerID=1154573520001&#038;playerKey=AQ~~,AAAAD2CGfQE~,o7E-F2eteXN94j8bb-0Zn7bFsvWVdC3l&#038;domain=embed&#038;dynamicStreaming=true" /><param name="base" value="//admin.brightcove.com" /><param name="seamlesstabbing" value="false" /><param name="allowFullScreen" value="true" /><param name="swLiveConnect" value="true" /><param name="allowScriptAccess" value="always" /><embed src="//c.brightcove.com/services/viewer/federated_f9?isVid=1&#038;isUI=1" bgcolor="#FFFFFF" flashVars="videoId=3467835402001&#038;playerID=1154573520001&#038;playerKey=AQ~~,AAAAD2CGfQE~,o7E-F2eteXN94j8bb-0Zn7bFsvWVdC3l&#038;domain=embed&#038;dynamicStreaming=true" base="//admin.brightcove.com" name="flashObj" width="250" height="220" seamlesstabbing="false" type="application/x-shockwave-flash" allowFullScreen="true" allowScriptAccess="always" swLiveConnect="true" pluginspage="//www.macromedia.com/shockwave/download/index.cgi?P1_Prod_Version=ShockwaveFlash"/></object></webonly></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Capital is the financial cornerstone of a bank. A bank with more capital can, in theory, absorb more losses and may be less vulnerable to a run. Ms. Yellen cited a 2010 study that said additional capital requirements would not weigh on the economy.</p>
<div class="entry entry-related"><h4>Related Links</h4>	<div class="entry-related">
		<ul>
					<li><a href="//www.federalreserve.gov/newsevents/speech/yellen20140415a.htm" title="Video and text of Yellen\'s speech"><img src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/multimedia/icons/video_icon.gif" alt="Video" width="12" height="9" border="0"> Video and Text of Yellen's Speech</a></li>
				</ul>
	</div>
	</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Daniel K. Tarullo, a Fed governor who oversees regulation, said nearly a year ago that the Fed was thinking of linking capital to short-term borrowing. The fact that it has continued to press this issue could send a chill through Wall Street firms, like <a href="//dealbook.on.nytimes.com/public/overview?symbol=GS&#038;inline=nyt-org" class="tickerized" title="More information about Goldman Sachs Group Inc">Goldman Sachs</a> and <a href="//dealbook.on.nytimes.com/public/overview?symbol=JPM&#038;inline=nyt-org" class="tickerized" title="More information about JPMorgan Chase &#038; Company">JPMorgan Chase</a>, that borrow billions of dollars a day in the short-term-debt market. Banks may oppose the measures out of self-interest. Holding more capital can make it harder for them to post the sort of returns that their shareholders expect. And these days, many bank executives receive a great deal of their compensation in stock.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Bankers may also argue that such regulations are overkill. Ms. Yellenâs speech follows the approval last week of a new rule, called the <a href="//dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/04/08/regulators-set-to-approve-new-capital-rule/">supplementary leverage ratio,</a> which could require the largest banks to find as much as $68 billion in extra capital over the next few years.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">If the Fed moves ahead with new regulations for short-term-debt markets, it will have to publish a draft of the proposed rules. This would give the banks a chance to criticize and lobby against what they do not like.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The industry is likely to push back against the argument that the economy will be fine even if the banks have to hold more capital. Donald N. Lamson, a partner at the law firm Shearman &#038; Sterling, said that when contemplating the new measures, regulators would have to consider whether reducing risks within the largest banks could undermine the creation of credit in the economy. âThose impulses are at odds,â Mr. Lamson said. âThey need to achieve the correct balance.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Bank lobbyists may also note that since the crisis, Wall Street firms have made much less use of the repurchase obligation, or repo, market. In this market, banks lend and borrow money for short periods against financial collateral like bonds. Although the repo market has shrunk, Mr. Tarullo said in November that banks and brokers had about $1.6 trillion in repo loans outstanding. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In her speech, Ms. Yellen said that additional regulation might be needed to address potential weaknesses in places like the repo market. Wall Street firms say that they try to closely match the money they borrow in the repo market with the repo loans they make to their clients. On the surface, that matching practice looks safe and balanced. But in panics, even the most carefully managed repo books can fall apart. That may happen when a Wall Street firm cannot raise money quickly enough to pay off its fleeing repo creditors. Runs in the repo market contributed heavily to the demise of <a href="//topics.nytimes.com/top/news/business/companies/lehman_brothers_holdings_inc/index.html?inline=nyt-org" class="tickerized" title="More articles about Lehman Brothers.">Lehman Brothers</a> and the near collapse of <a href="//topics.nytimes.com/top/news/business/companies/bear_stearns_companies/index.html?inline=nyt-org" class="tickerized" title="More information about Bear Stearns Cos">Bear Stearns</a>. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">When many banks faced this sort of cash crunch in 2008, the Fed stepped in and lent them billions of dollars in replacement funds. To critics of Wall Street, the loans from the Fed were an enormous stealth bailout. The Fed has defended the loans, arguing that central banks are supposed to provide emergency loans to banks in stressed times to contain panic and protect the wider economy.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Still, Ms. Yellenâs remarks on the need to bolster short-term-debt markets indicate that the Fed does not want to be put in a position where it would have to provide loans on that scale again. âTogether,â Ms. Yellen said, âthese runs were the primary engine of a financial crisis from which the United States and the global economy have yet to fully recover.â</p>
<footer class="story-footer">
    <div class="story-meta">
	<p class="story-print-citation">A version of this article appears in print on 04/16/2014, on page <span itemprop="printSection">B</span><span itemprop="printPage">3</span> of the <span itemprop="printEdition">NewYork</span> edition with the headline: Yellen Suggests That Fed Will Push to Shore Up Market for Short-Term Debt.</p>    </div>
